\section*{Exponential Distribution and Decay Factor}

The core of the exponential distribution is e , the natural logarithm in an exponential function with the variable $-\frac{x}{\mu}$ in the exponent. The exponent is negative, and thus it describes an exponentially declining function as we have seen in Figure 5.13, Figure 5.14, and Figure 5.15 above.

This gives rise to an alternative formula for the exponential probability distribution:
$$\begin{gathered}
f(x)=m e^{-m} \\
F(x)=\int_{0}^{x} m e^{-m t} d t=1-e^{-m x}
\end{gathered}$$

Where $m=\frac{1}{\mu}$ is given the name decay factor and measures the speed of decay. The decay factor simply measures how rapidly the probability of an event declines as the random variable $X$ increases.
$$P\left(x_{a} \leq x_{1}\right) P\left(x_{b} \leq x_{1}\right) P\left(x_{c} \leq x_{1}\right)=$$

